Looking at the `TimeZoneDisplayKey` class in the file, I can see the issue. The constructor receives 4 parameters (TimeZone, daylight, style, locale), but in the equals method, it's not checking the daylight parameter as part of the equality. Let me look closer:

The constructor does:
```java
TimeZoneDisplayKey(TimeZone timeZone, boolean daylight, int style, Locale locale) {
    mTimeZone = timeZone;
    if (daylight) {
        style |= 0x80000000;  // This is the key - daylight info is encoded in the style
    }
    mStyle = style;
    mLocale = locale;
}
```

And the equals method does:
```java
public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    if (this == obj) {
        return true;
    }
    if (obj instanceof TimeZoneDisplayKey) {
        TimeZoneDisplayKey other = (TimeZoneDisplayKey)obj;
        return
            mTimeZone.equals(other.mTimeZone) &&
            mStyle == other.mStyle &&
            mLocale.equals(other.mLocale);
    }
    return false;
}
```

The problem is that when the object is deserialized, the `mStyle` field contains the encoded daylight information as part of the style value, but when deserializing, this encoded value might not be handled correctly. Let me run the test to see the actual error:

